labels.label: Transorm data from stage tables into core tables
Start ETL

Philosophy/Principles Of My Approach.
a) Every logical block (Process Group) must have onle and only one input and one and only one input flow file
b) If you have to copy a parts of the workflow somewhere else to do the same thing think about your workflow. Is there a way to do in more nicely, to have everything on onel place ? exception: logging PGs
Abbreviations PG - processor grouop
If any error occurs during etl process a) send email b) clean up and prepare everything for the next load
Notes: This workflow was created for a classical data warehouse approach. start -> fetch data to stage tables -> execute stageToCore transformations -> execute coreToMart transformations

General Notes: * Naming Convention:
** connections - all lowercase with spaces - "this is a connection name" Idealy use only 3 names for connections: "in" - input "success" - success output "error" - error output
* Never use gobal variables. Always set variables using the UpdateAttribute processor. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Break this rule only if there is no other way. Think twice if it wouldn't be better to have 2 levels of routing anbd each level is either 'success' or 'error'. I broke this rule once. See routing on ${workflowCode} in processor groups "Set Path, Query, ....", "Extract IDs" and "Parse Response"

processGroups.comments:
This flow will track how many times a given flow file routes through it. If the number of times exceeds a specific maximum then it will route to the 'limit exceeded' port. Otherwise it will route to 'retry'.
The attributes it uses are 'retry.counter' and 'retry.maxcount'. If the 'retry.maxcount' is specified on a given flowfile then it will be honored. Otherwise a default of '3' is set as the maximum retry count.
As the flowfile goes through this flow it increments the 'retry.maxcount' attribute by 1. It then checks if this value exceeds 'retry.maxcount' and if so then it routes the flowfile to 'limit exceeded' otherwise it routes to 'retry'.
So you can configure the 'retry' relationship to loop back to the process you want and you can send the 'limit exceeded' to move on from that process to something else.

outputPorts.comments: Items sent to this port have not yet exceeded the maximum retry count.
outputPorts.name: retry

labels.label: Create 2 FF. One - will start the data ingest Second - will wait for a given time (Until data ingest 'probably' ends). After that time it will be routed to either 'success' or 'error'

Note: *It's not possible to know how many flow files will be created during data ingest.* At least I wasn't able to think of a way to do that. Therefore we can't use wait/notify pattern.
What I've done instead: 1. Give the workflow enough time to finish. 2. Drop FFs that fetched data sucessfully and keep only error FFs. 3. After wait time expires, check if there were error FFs. If not assumee that everything worked as expected and continute ETL process. -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Example: Workflow starts at 08:00. You've measured that the data ingest process takes 10 mins. Set processor that waits until the ETL finishes to start at 08:20. (give it some buffer time) at 08:20 two thigs can occcur: 1. There is only 1 FF( the one that has been waiting since 08:00). Route that FF into 'success' connection 2. There is more than 1 FF. Merge them into one FF and route that FF into 'error' connection If at the input of that processror is more that 1 FF then something
